    {
      "id": "6386962c2dae40d79194a83447957a976a122681",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2012-09-22 18:16:36.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5: Verified\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.3/x86_64, CentOS release 5.8/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/84e26ba2-04de-11e2-bfd4-52540035b04c).  Ran 12 tests.  No failures.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "220cfa07cd1675d86a712d90820205bd0de86437",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 116,
        "name": "Brian J. Murrell",
        "email": "brian.murrell@intel.com",
        "username": "brian",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-09-23 18:51:28.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4: (1 inline comment)\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "4d90c91f4b077b7c01e71f6c64e62afea81cdf80",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-09-23 19:54:08.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(2 inline comments)\n\nI agree with Brian - having more config options just makes it more complex to get correct.  Why not just add multiple \"-I\" directories to handle the difference between in-tree and RPM header locations?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "56354d0f6347bce2e06d624036174a12f654bea1",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 116,
        "name": "Brian J. Murrell",
        "email": "brian.murrell@intel.com",
        "username": "brian",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-09-24 11:02:35.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nThe problem I see with just stacking up -I specifications is that a user might have both (-devel and source tree) installed and might want to choose which to build with.  With stacking -I specifications, whichever we put first on the gcc line will always be the one used.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "67a48488d09d74ffaf73aa3564471300e421e985",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2012-09-24 16:25:33.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5: (2 inline comments)\n\nI have to agree with Brian. I can see also where the headers from the source versus the ones installed from rpm become out of sync as well. What the does compiler do then? So IMO it's safe to pick one or the other.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "6dbb1caa22c85b762058fe08d39bfe5dfbef8940",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-09-25 06:44:51.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nTo clarify my previous statements - my goal is not to add -I includes for both the build and install path simultaneously. Only to smooth over the differences between the include path once the --with-zfs path is specified (or defaulted). In one case the include files are under libzfs, and in the other case they are not.\n\nWhat I'm suggesting is something like:\n\n  -I $ZFS/libzfs -I $ZFS\n\n(with details corrected as needed, since I'm replying from my phone and cannot check).",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "1d7abd5c99691a0c84fd3e3531e706bfd524f867",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2012-09-25 12:59:18.000000000",
      "message": "Uploaded patch set 6.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "23e4e4caefeeb6305728420cd67aa2496dee584c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 2,
        "name": "Jenkins",
        "username": "hudson",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-09-25 12:59:21.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nBuild Started http://build.whamcloud.com/job/lustre-reviews/9414/ ",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "624179820f7ce7df395453af376657fd56bfa99c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2012-09-25 13:18:04.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nBuilding --with-[spl/zfs]=path where path is the source code tree then yes you can do \n\n$ZFS_DIR/lib/libspl/include -I $ZFS_DIR/include\n\n-------------------------------------------------------\nThe problem is if you use the rpms. In that case the headers for the kernel modules are stored in \n\n$ZFS_DIR/$SPL_DIR\n\nlibzfs/libspl headers are stored in \n\n/usr/include/libzfs\n/usr/include/libspl \n\nAlso this patch handles the case of building lustre on a build box without the zfs-devel rpms installed. Since the user might not have super user access he/she needs to point the build system to another place to where the user land headers can be installed i.e /tmp for example.\n\nYes its a mess.See https://github.com/zfsonlinux/zfs/issues/453",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "09118ca5bcc786c0383a768b109a746d809656c5",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 2,
        "name": "Jenkins",
        "username": "hudson",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-09-25 13:18:42.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6: Verified\n\nBuild Successful \n \nhttp://build.whamcloud.com/job/lustre-reviews/9414/ : SUCCESS",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "817622540296d468a721d4e9b9d9ef7204743527",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 116,
        "name": "Brian J. Murrell",
        "email": "brian.murrell@intel.com",
        "username": "brian",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-09-25 14:08:25.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(1 inline comment)\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "a94cdae8669935181f8e46b0130bd0bd139e53d1",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2012-09-25 14:33:26.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6: (1 inline comment)\n\nSince everyone is against having another configure option how about expanding --with-zfs to accept multiple directorys. One to point to the ZFS kernel headers and another to point to zfs library headers. Would this be acceptable to everyone?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "99d2a1accf15b5ae75b2d73ed602a6188a062a84",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2012-09-25 17:39:49.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nAnother option is to have --with-zfs point to the source tree and zfs-obj point to the kernel headers. Need to update lbuild to handle this tho.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "ea4bc14c9d24a5b8ad84cbba49af853846ec91b2",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 116,
        "name": "Brian J. Murrell",
        "email": "brian.murrell@intel.com",
        "username": "brian",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-09-25 19:07:51.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nThis is all discussion that should go in the ticket, not in reviews, so please follow up there... however...\n\nI don't understand why we'd need both --with-zfs and --zfs-obj.  Are the kernel headers not in the zfs source tree?  I thought the zfs modules were built in the zfs source tree so surely the zfs kernel headers should be in there also, yes?\n\nIdeally there is one switch, --with-zfs.  It has the following values:\n\n1. yes\n  - build using system installed zfs-devel package\n2. no\n  - not interested in any zfs support at all\n3. /path/to/unpacked-devel\n  - inspect /path/to/... to determine if it's an unpacked\n    zfs-devel package and set variables accordingly to direct\n    the compiler and linker to finding the products it needs\n    under the /path/to/unpacked-devel path\n4. /path/to/zfs/source/tree\n  - inspect /path/to/... to determine if it's a zfs source\n    tree and set variables accordingly to direct the\n    compiler and linker to finding the products it needs\n    under the /path/to/zfs/source/tree path\n\nIs there some reason this cannot work?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
